pgTitle: List of WCW World Heavyweight Champions

rows.text: Defeated Steamboat in a rematch. Aired on May 14, 1994.
This was Hogan's first match in WCW.
The Giant was stripped due to controversial finish of Halloween Havoc match.

During this rematch from last night's Starrcade, referee Randy Anderson was knocked unconscious and Nick Patrick came down, counted Sting's shoulders down and awarded the title to Hogan. After the match a brawl ensued during which Anderson came to thinking the match was still going on and attempted to award the bout to Sting. But no bell could be heard as the match had already officially ended when Patrick called for the bell. Sting however left with the belt while Hogan still claimed to be champion. The ending of this match was not shown on TV until the following Thursday.
Aired January 8, 1998. Held up due to controversy over finish of December 28 and December 29 matches.
Defeated Flair, Sting, and Hollywood Hogan in a four-way match.
Defeated Sting, Kevin Nash, and Goldberg in a No Disqualification Fatal Four-Way match.
Savage pinned Nash in a tag team match also featuring Sid Vicious and Sting; if Nash was pinned or if he had to submit he would lose the championship.
Hogan originally won the title under his nWo style "Hollywood" gimmick, but midway through his reign reverted back to his classic, red & yellow "Hulkamania" gimmick
Hart vacates the title due to injury.
Benoit forfeits the title and leaves for the WWF after dispute with management.
Defeated Nash and Ron Harris in a handicap match by making Nash submit. Aired January 26, 2000.
Defeated Dallas Page in tournament final.
Defeated Jeff Jarrett in a Cage Match
Won in a Triple Cage match that also included Page.
Vince Russo stripped Flair of the title.
Defeats Jarrett and Scott Steiner in a Triple Threat match. Aired on May 24, 2000.
Nash gave title back to Flair.
On orders from Vince Russo, Jarrett laid down in the ring and allowed Hogan to pin him for the championship. After which an argument ensues between Hogan and Russo.
After the controversial Hogan/Jarrett match, head writer Vince Russo announced that Jarrett would defend the title in an impromptu match against Booker T.
Russo decides he is not a wrestler and he does not want the title.
Won in a "Straight Jacket steel cage match".
